The Gloamvault is the Kel'Shadra Order's central archive, built as the Vault of Last Witness: a subterranean chapel-archive where testimony, vow, sentence, and burial would remain physically bound together, making the dead available as evidence. The Order arose from a confederation of cemetery chaplains, battlefield notaries, and funeral archivists sharing the conviction that unrecorded oaths destroyed legal memory: inheritance collapsed when witnesses died, trade agreements vanished when oathkeepers were killed, surrender terms were renegotiated by victors claiming misremembering. Vault-Mother Hesparine of the Seventh Bell established the triune doctrine: What is witnessed must be named; what is named must be offered; what is offered must be bound. Three interlocked offices controlled the vault: the Bell Synod (ritual clergy managing entry and admissible memory), the Ash Scriptorium (archivists turning testimony into binding record), and the Reliquary Host (martial custodians enforcing compliance). In practice, each weaponized the others: clergy withheld absolution unless records were favorable, scriveners delayed records to force political outcomes, guards staged accidents to resolve disputes before they reached testimony. The Riven Gate event — the Night of Unsounded Bells — was an internal purge: reformist Scriptorium archivists attempted to expose falsified absolution records for high-ranking donors. The Reliquary Host split; emergency ward pylons were detonated at the gate; the vault fractured into jurisdictions that never recovered. Bell-Matriarch Velastra stabilized the aftermath by standardizing cruelty: merging confession intake with sentencing queues, reclassifying dissent as memory contamination, converting archive penalties into labor assignments. The Gloamvault connects downward to the Crypts of Kel'Shadra — sequential filters, not separate institutions.

