Midgaard's relationship to the Gloamvault is institutionally complex. The Order's archive function — neutral witness, recorded oath, certified burial — was genuinely useful to Midgaard's merchant class and legal apparatus in the period before the city's own registry systems were robust. Many historical Midgaard inheritance disputes cite Kel'Shadra records as primary evidence. Post-collapse, Midgaard's position is that the Gloamvault constitutes a partially abandoned archive under unclear jurisdictional status: the Order's governance claims lapsed with the Night of Unsounded Bells, but the physical records remain, and some of them are the only surviving documentation of pre-Compact legal transactions. The sealed warrants system Midgaard uses for sensitive administrative records drew on Kel'Shadra procedural vocabulary — the "bell-line" language in sealed warrant protocols is a direct inheritance. Midgaard's current concern is access to specific Gloamvault records for ongoing legal proceedings: requests routed through the Continuity office's vault-access protocol encounter the same problem they always do — the Order's surviving Continuance Clergy treat all access requests as requiring Synod-level authorization, from a Synod that has no legitimate external authority.

