Kiess's founding charter includes the clause that "no sealed warrant issued by a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen" — a clause written in direct response to Kel'Shadra's practice of issuing warrants under predecessor legal frameworks to transfer condemned persons. The Gloamvault's operations, and specifically its "descent accounting" practice of routing persons through the vault into the Crypts without civic remainder, are the historical practice Kiess formally repudiated at its founding. Kiess therefore treats the Gloamvault not as an accessible archive but as a documented case of institutional corruption — the clearest historical example of what oath-recording systems become when they accumulate authority without accountability. The Temple of Concord in Kiess incorporates accounts of the Night of Unsounded Bells into cautionary sermons about institutional failure, drawing parallels between the Conclave's accountability failures in the Cinderteeth and the Kel'Shadra's accountability failures in the Gloamvault.

