Khenari death-rite geography treats the Gloamvault as a site where the boundary between proper and improper funerary practice was systematically violated. The Order's triune doctrine, in Khenari reading, was sound in its original form: naming the dead, recording what they owed and were owed, and binding those records to material remains is a legitimate funerary function. The corruption was the weaponization of the binding stage — treating the dead's legal records as instruments of living institutional politics rather than as closed accounts. The Correction sentence class (memory rewritten for political continuity) is, from a Khenari perspective, the worst possible outcome: not merely death, but identity theft, with the dead's testimony restructured to serve the interests of those who survived them. The Night of Unsounded Bells — the moment the vault turned on itself — is preserved in Khenari oral tradition as the inevitable consequence of treating death records as leverage.
